4 User stories
• As a passenger, I want to submit a request based on my location and preferred time slot, so I can find
a carpool to the office.
• As a driver, I want to create an offer based on my available time slots, location, number of seats, and
flexibility, so I can help my coworkers with carpooling.
• As a general user, I want to chat with co-riders with whom I matched, so that I can coordinate pick-ups.
• As a user, I want to save my frequent routes, so I can post or search for carpool options more quickly
in the future.
• As a priority passenger, I want to ensure I can secure a ride before others, so I can get to the office on
time.
• As a user, I want to receive notifications when the system finds a match for me, so I don’t have to
search for it myself.
• As a user, I want to join social rides, so I can meet and connect with new colleagues.
• As a passenger, I want rides closest to my location to appear at the top of the list, so I can easily
choose the most convenient option.
• As a user, if I traveled to work with a colleague, I want an easy way to arrange the return trip with
the same person.
• As a passenger, I want to be notified if my planned ride is canceled, so I can quickly find an alternative
way to get to work.
5 Usage scenarios
5.1 Passenger requests a drive
1. Ismaël needs to travel from Louvain-la-neuve to the Odoo workplace for a meeting.
2. He opens the carpooling app and selects “Request a ride”.
3. He fills in his trip details: departure at 08:00 from Louvain-la-neuve Gare des Bus to his workplace at
Odoo.
4. The app searches for compatible rides.
5. The system finds 3 available rides since Ismaël has selected the “social ride” option the system matches
him up with drivers he does not know yet.
6. Ismaël reviews the list and selects a ride offered by a driver named Ingrid.
7. He sends a request to join Ingrid’s ride.
8. The system confirms his request and sends Ingrid a notification.
8
5.2 Driver posts a ride
1. Ingrid plans to drive from Louvain-la-neuve to her workplace at Odoo on Friday.
2. She opens the app and selects “Publish a ride”.
3. She fills in her departure details: departure at 08:00 from Louvain-la-neuve Gare des Bus to her
workplace at Odoo.
4. The system checks for existing passenger requests on that route.
5. It finds two passengers looking for rides at similar times.
6. One passenger has a “priority” status which makes their request appear first.
7. Ingrid reviews the passenger requests and accepts both.
8. The system updates the number of seats available and confirms the ride.
9. Both passengers receive a notification confirming their seats.
5.3 Use case
5.3.1 Passenger requests a drive
1. Passenger opens the carpooling app.
2. Passenger selects the option to “Publish a ride request”.
3. Passenger fills in the form with their trip data and submits it.
4. System validates the form and searches for compatible rides.
5. If no compatible rides are found, the system shows the closest available options.
6. If compatible rides are found, the system checks if the passenger has selected “social ride” or not.
7. System displays the available ride options according to the passenger’s preferences.
8. Passenger selects one of the rides.
9. Passenger sends a request to join the selected ride.
10. System confirms the request and notifies the corresponding driver.
5.3.2 Driver posts a ride
1. Driver opens the carpooling app.
2. Driver selects the option to “Publish a ride”.
3. Driver fills out the form with the trip data
4. System validates the form with the input data.
5. System searches for matching passenger requests.
6. If no matches are found, the system puts the ride on hold for passengers to view later.
7. If matches are found, the system identifies any priority passengers and moves them to the top of the
request list.
9
8. The system displays the requests in FIFO order.
9. Driver views the list of passenger requests.
10. Driver chooses to accept or ignore each passenger’s request.
11. If a request is accepted then the system updates the number of seats, confirms the reservation and
sends a notification to the passengers.
6 Wireframes
Figure 10: Wireframe of a proposed "All Rides" map view. On the left the potential passenger can see all
available rides, with the map view on the right visualising the details of a particullar trip. The list on the
left is sorted according to the preferences for addresses/zones that were put in previously. Floating buttons
on the map view allow to reserve the chosen ride or message the responsible driver.
10
Figure 11: Wireframe of the ’All Rides’ thread view interface. The columns show details of different rides,
such as the name of the driver, departure zone, departure time, destination zone, and available seats. Users
can search for rides using the search bar, add a new ride by clicking the ’New’ button, and interact with
the driver or reserve a seat using the available buttons. The star logo indicates that the driver has priority
passengers in the ride. The social ride button acts as a filter to show only rides where the driver and requester
have never carpooled together before.
Figure 12: Wireframe of the ’All Requests’ thread view interface. The columns show details of different ride
requests, such as the name of the requester, departure zone, departure time, destination zone, and action
buttons. Users can search for requests using the search bar, add a new request by clicking the ’New’ button,
and interact with each request by using the available ’Add’ or ’Ignore’ buttons. The star logo indicates that
the requester has priority status for this request. The ’Social Ride’ button acts as a filter to display only
requests from users who have never shared a ride with the current user before.
